@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction to pEditor"

@{b}@{u}Introduction to pEditor@{uu}@{ub}

pEditor is a simple MUI based text editor for the Amiga.

It is released as freeware and as a preview of the new textediting class that I'm developing to use in webPlug v2.

It's simple, and it will stay like this. Don't expect major new features in future releases of the program, since pEditor is (int it's current form) just a testbed for the class. Anyway I'm open to the addition of features, and new versions of the program will appear. Again, the class is for webPlug and my other programs.
@endnode

@node FEATURES "Features"

@{b}@{u}pEditor features@{uu}@{ub}

Here goes an small list of features:

- Handles large texts with no noticeable slowdown.

- Supports real tabs (they are not converted to spaces).

- Macro recording and playing.

- Case sensitive/insensitive find and replace commands.

- Text selecting, and cut/copy/paste from/to the standard clipboard.

- You can drag selected areas of text around.

- Automatic text indenting.

- The main window is an appwindow. Just drag a file's icon to load it.

- Configurable colors, font, cursor blinking and other settings.

The class _supports_ realtime syntax highlightning, but this feature will be included (actually enabled) in webPlug v2, and is not planned for pEditor.
HTML parsers already exists and work quite well :)
Other parsers are of course possible, although there are no plans by now to do them myself.

I'm starting to consider to upgrade pEditor to a powerfull editor, with parsers for some languages, but I have tons of work with wP, mP and other projects. It depends, as always, on the feedback and support from you.
@endnode

@node REQUIRE "What do I need ?"

@{b}@{u}What do I need ?@{uu}@{ub}

In order to run pEditor, you need:

- An Amiga (or compatible :) computer with at least AmigaOS v3.0 (I'm not 100% sure... it may run on v2.x).

- MUI 3.8 correctly installed.
@endnode

@node USING "Using pEditor"

@{b}@{u}Using pEditor@{uu}@{ub}

You can start pEditor by doubleclicking its' icon in the workbench, or from a Shell. In this case, you can specify which file to load.

The program is (I hope) intuitive and easy to use, but anyway here goes a little description of the options:

  @{"The editor" link using0}
  @{"The toolbar" link using1}
  @{"The menus" link using2}
  @{"The prefs window" link using3}

@endnode

@node USING0 "Using pEditor"

 Using the editor
-=====-===-======-

Using the editor is quite straightforward. Here just goes a list of key shortcuts:

ALT LEFT		Previous word
ALT RIGHT		Next word
ALT UP			Previous page
ALT DOWN		Next word
CTRL LEFT		End of line
CTRL RIGHT		Begin of line
CTRL UP			Top
CTRL DOWN		Bottom
ALT BACKSPACE	Delete to begin of word
ALT DEL		Delete to end of word
CTRL BACKSPACE	Delete to begin of line
CTRL DEL			Delete to end of line
CTRL X			Delete the current line

This keys will be configurable in a future version of the program.

@endnode

@node USING1 "Using pEditor"

 The toolbar
-===-=======-

Ok. From left to right:

-Clear current text
-Load a new text
-Save current text
-Save current text to a new file
-Save current text and quit

-Cut selection to the clipboard
-Copy selection to the clipboard
-Paste text from the clipboard

-Record macro

This option will record all your actions to an internal buffer so that they can be later reproduced.
Several things:

	* Load/Save operations are not recorded.
	  If you perform such an operation, the recording is stopped.
	* Find and replace buffers _are_ stored, but due to some reasons, only their first line. This is not likely to change.

-Play macro

Plays a previously recorded macro. You can leave the button pressed so that the macro will be played repeatedly.

@endnode

@node USING2 "Using pEditor"

 The menus
-===-=====-

[PENDING]

@endnode

@node USING3 "Using pEditor"

 The prefs window
-===-=====-======-

You can control some of the features of pEditor.
The options are currently divided in 2 sections:

General:

Font - The font/size that pEditor will use. Only fixed-width fonts are possible.
Colors - The colors that pEditor will use to display the text. Try to restrict the pens you'll be using if you're working on an AGA screen with 6+ bitplanes.

Misc:

EOL Char - You can enter here a char that pEditor will display at the end of each line.
Automatic line indenting - When active, pEditor will indent each new line you create. This is specially usefull when creating a source.
Hold X position - The X position (column) of the cursor will be keeped by pEditor even if a line is shorter than this position (?).
Move cursor with sliders - If you move the text up and down (or left and right) with the sliders, the cursor will "follow" it if this option is enabled.

Tab size - The number of spaces that pEditor will use for each tab char.
Cursor blink speed - Lets you adjust the speed of the cursor blink or turn it off.

@endnode

